<p>I use VirtualBox and do some testing and learning with multiple machines running at once.</p>
<p>Usually those machines are servers so I don&rsquo;t really need the GUI since I connecting to them using SSH clinet.</p>
<p>When VirtualBox is installed you&rsquo;ll see <code>VBoxManage</code> executable (<code>vboxmanage</code> is also there as alias) which is CLI tool
that allows you to interact with your VMs.</p>
<p>Here is a command how you can start VM in headless mode:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span style="display:flex;"><span>vboxmanage startvm &lt;vm name&gt; --type headless
</span></span></code></pre></div><br/>
Pretty simple.
<p>To shutdown the VM run this:</p>
<div class="highlight"><pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;"><code class="language-bash" data-lang="bash"><span style="display:flex;"><span>vboxmanage controlvm &lt;vm name&gt; poweroff
</span></span></code></pre></div><br/>
That's it. You can also run `vboxmanage` without any params to get list of all options/actions it supports.
<p>Have fun.</p>